AWS E-Commerce Platform — AquaMart (Full-Stack)

A production-style e-commerce application deployed end-to-end on AWS.
It includes a secure static frontend, backend API, database, custom domain, SSL, and complete cloud infrastructure following best practices.

Live Project: https://aquamart.dpdns.org

1. Project Overview

Frontend: React app hosted on Amazon S3, delivered via CloudFront using Origin Access Control (OAC).

Backend: Node.js & Express running on an EC2 instance with IAM roles for secure DynamoDB access.

Database: DynamoDB tables for users, products, and orders.

Domain & SSL: Managed through Route 53 and secured with ACM certificates.

Security: IAM least-privilege policies, private S3 buckets, strict EC2 Security Groups.

2. AWS Architecture

User → CloudFront → S3 (Frontend) + EC2 API → DynamoDB

CloudFront (CDN + HTTPS)
          ↓
S3 Bucket (Frontend Hosting)
          ↓
User ←───────→ EC2 (Node.js API) ←→ DynamoDB

3. Frontend (S3 + CloudFront + HTTPS + OAC)
Steps

Build React app:

cd frontend
npm install
npm run build


Create S3 bucket (public access blocked).

Upload build folder to S3.

Create CloudFront distribution:

Origin: S3 bucket

OAC enabled

Default root object: index.html

Attach HTTPS certificate from ACM.

Invalidate CloudFront cache when deploying updates.

Screenshots

S3 bucket

ACM certificate

4. Domain & DNS (Route 53)
Steps

Create Hosted Zone for your domain.

Add A/AAAA alias record pointing to CloudFront.

Add ACM validation CNAME.

Wait for DNS propagation.

Screenshot

Route 53 hosted zone

5. Backend API (EC2 + IAM Role + Security Groups)
Steps

Launch EC2 Ubuntu instance.

Attach an IAM role with DynamoDB permissions.

Configure Security Group:

22 → SSH

80 → HTTP

443 → HTTPS

5000 → Backend API

Install Node.js & PM2:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install nodejs npm -y


Clone and start backend:

git clone https://github.com/Pakthapriyan/Aquamart-Website
cd backend
npm install
pm2 start npm -- start


(Optional) Configure Nginx reverse proxy.

Screenshot

EC2 Security Group rules

6. Database (DynamoDB)

Tables created:

Table	Partition Key
Users	userId
Products	productId
Orders	orderId
